<p>On the other end, industries with the lowest cost per lead were Restaurants and Food ($3.16), Real Estate ($16.61), and Career and Employment ($17.64).</p>
<p>For businesses on the higher end of the CPL spectrum, like Dentists and Dental Services and Health and Fitness, people tend to spend more on these types of services. So, a higher CPL in this case correlates with higher value leads.</p>
<p>‚ÄúRegardless of the advertising platform, we‚Äôre starting to see cost-related metrics rise. CPL is the main metric many businesses look to as a core KPI on Facebook, and it‚Äôs gone up by 20% this year. However, just because prices are rising doesn‚Äôt mean businesses should necessarily pare down their advertising,‚Äù Tyler said.</p>
<p>‚ÄúIn fact, businesses that can afford to remain in the market will become more visible, since a lot of competition tends to pull back on advertising in harsh economic times,‚Äù Tyler said.</p>
<h4>Average cost per lead: YoY</h4>
<p>The biggest cost per lead increases year over year were found in industries such as Arts and Entertainment, which increased by 242%, Dentists and Dental Services, which increased by 97%, and Industrial and Commercial, which increased by 62%.</p>
<p>The industries that saw the biggest declines in CPL were Restaurants and Food, down 93%, Attorneys and Legal Services, down 77%, and Furniture, down 31%.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/2025-fb-benchmarks-leads-cpl-yoy-917x1024.webp" alt="2025 facebook ads benchmarks - cost per lead year over year" width="917" height="1024" class="aligncenter wp-image-93931 size-large" /></p>
<div id="improve-meta-ads"></div>
<h2>Facebook ads tips for any business</h2>
<p>If your Facebook ads results don‚Äôt match the data for your industry above, don‚Äôt worry. Here are our top tips for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/09/26/how-to-optimize-facebook-ads" target="_blank" rel="noopener">how to improve your Facebook ads</a>.</p>
<h3>Use Advantage+ carefully (and sometimes sparingly)</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/meta-advantage-vs-manual-settings" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Advantage+ is a suite of AI-powered features</a> advertisers can apply to their campaigns, ad sets, and ads. Advantage+ can help streamline your ad creation and targeting. However, there are some<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/meta-advantage-plus" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> pros and cons to be aware of</a>. Using Advantage+ can sway your Facebook ads results if you‚Äôre not 100% confident in the data you feed it to help guide and optimize your campaigns.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/meta-ads-benchmarks-advantage-plus.webp" alt="meta ads benchmarks - advantage+ infopage screenshot" width="842" height="327" class="aligncenter wp-image-93946 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/meta-ads-benchmarks-advantage-plus.webp 842w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/meta-ads-benchmarks-advantage-plus-480x186.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 842px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>‚ÄúYou will likely see better metrics in your Meta advertising reports with Advantage+, but who are you actually advertising to? My suggestion is to either use Advantage+ sparingly or have quality control in place to limit the amount of bots that submit forms,‚Äù said Brett McHale, founder of<a href="https://empiricmarketing.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> Empiric Marketing</a>.</p>
<p>For example, you could have your forms block specific email domains or phone numbers to limit lead spam and keep your lead quality high when implementing Advantage+ targeting.</p>
<p><strong><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4a1.png" alt="üí°" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Incorporating AI into your advertising strategy can be tricky.</strong> Find out how to do it right with these <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/ai-advertising?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_AIAdvertising_Download&amp;itm_source=wordstream&amp;itm_medium=blog&amp;itm_campaign=incontent_links" target="_blank" rel="noopener">9 powerful ways to use AI in Facebook and Google Ads</a>!</p>
<h3>Focus on lead <em>quality</em> over quantity</h3>
<p>Speaking of lead quality, you‚Äôll want your lead types to be top of mind when building out your Facebook ads campaigns. Consider your ideal audience members and tailor your ads to them specifically, rather than going after the whole crowd.</p>
<p>‚ÄúThe most important metric for success is who you are driving actions from, or in other words, lead quality. You have to be twice as diligent about targeting and campaign settings to ensure you are targeting the highest quality users possible,‚Äù Brett said.</p>
<p>While this tip applies across all campaign objectives, this is especially true for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-to-optimize-facebook-lead-ads" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Facebook leads campaigns</a>.</p>
<p>‚ÄúTraffic campaigns are getting more efficient, which is great to see, but the rise in CPL for Lead Ads shows that getting quality leads is tougher than it used to be.¬† It‚Äôs not just about getting clicks anymore, it‚Äôs about making sure those clicks actually convert,‚Äù said Cliff Sizemore, Senior Marketing Manager at LocaliQ.</p>
<h3>Keep your goals top of mind</h3>
<p>It can be easy to get lost in the sauce when you‚Äôre analyzing specific metrics at a granular level. However, try not to lose sight of your overall Facebook advertising goals. All of the metrics in your account paint a bigger picture of your overall account health when looked at in tandem with one another.</p>
<p>‚ÄúA single metric does not necessarily determine a campaign&#8217;s success. Your business‚Äôs advertising outcomes typically depend on your overall objectives,‚Äù said Mat Wendler, Senior Manager of Optimization Strategy and Custom Solutions at LocaliQ.</p>
<p>‚ÄúFor instance, you could have a low cost per lead, but the number of qualified leads may still be insufficient, potentially impacting your business‚Äôs advertising results. Each metric provides information about the campaign&#8217;s performance, and it is the responsibility of the advertiser and their marketing partners to interpret their significance,‚Äù Mat said.</p>
<p>So, whether or not a specific metric is doing great or in need of improvement, try to think about how it could be related to other performance indicators and your overall account health.</p>
<p>‚ÄúIt‚Äôs incredibly rare that a well-tuned campaign meeting or exceeding benchmarks isn‚Äôt providing value for a business. That said, given the fact that most metrics are taking a hit this year due to economic headwinds, it‚Äôs more important than ever to scrutinize every data point and ensure marketing dollars are producing more than just good metrics,‚Äù Tyler said.</p>
<p>It‚Äôs also good to remember here that no two Facebook ad accounts are exactly alike‚Äîand what might work for one business might not for another.</p>
<p>‚ÄúThe metric that matters most is the one that ties directly to your goals. All others can be helpful indicators, but the one we need to prioritize over all the others is the main goal,‚Äù said Michelle Morgan, Co-Founder of <a href="https://www.paidmediapros.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Paid Media Pros</a>.</p>
<p>‚ÄúFor those trying to generate more business sales, that ties directly to conversion rate, cost per lead, and return on ad spend. For those trying to attract and engage new audiences, that‚Äôs likely more focused on CTR and CPC. It‚Äôs all case dependent, but just because a metric is important to another business owner or marketer, doesn‚Äôt mean it needs to be a priority for you,‚Äù Michelle said.</p>
<h3>Use a mix of campaign objectives</h3>
<p>While the leads and traffic objectives are the pillars of most <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/scale-meta-ads-with-first-party-data" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Meta advertising strategies</a>, don‚Äôt forget there are a few other campaign objective options. All the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/facebook-ad-objectives" target="_blank" rel="noopener">different Facebook ads campaign objectives</a> complement each other, so try to include a variety of campaign types in your account.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/facebook-ad-objectives-e1749239041209.webp" alt="facebook ad objectives" width="419" height="515" class="aligncenter wp-image-84952 size-full" /></p>
<p>‚ÄúFacebook provides a range of advertising objectives. It is a common misconception that advertisers should focus solely on the objective aligned with their final goal. For instance, if the intended outcome is to generate leads, it may be beneficial to consider running branding and traffic campaigns in addition to a lead campaign,‚Äù Mat said.</p>
<p>‚ÄúSmall and medium-sized businesses might not have substantial brand recognition, which can impact their ability to attract leads right off the bat. Facebook&#8217;s platform offers tools to support both branding and lead generation within a single source,‚Äù Mat said.</p>
<p>Testing a mix of campaign objectives and ad types in your strategy also helps you balance out any performance gaps.</p>
<p>‚ÄúAll of these metrics play together, and you have to balance them out for your own goals. The most common misalignment I hear is expecting a high CTR and high CVR, especially for lead generation companies. You‚Äôre likely going to see decreasing CTRs (and increasing CPCs) as you focus in on your audience and improve your CVR. This is just part of the lead quality game that we all play,‚Äù Michelle said.</p>
<p>‚ÄúWhen you‚Äôre ad copy testing and looking to drive high-quality leads, don‚Äôt be discouraged by lower CTRs. Keep things in a manageable range but be flexible with where your CTR ends up. Be willing to sacrifice a few points here and there to make it up on the back end and in your bank account,‚Äù Michelle said.</p>
<h3>Prioritize your unique value proposition in ad copy and creative</h3>
<p>You want to take users on a journey through your sales funnel when they view and interact with your ads. Focus on engaging and enriching ads that will convey your brand messaging in a unique way.</p>
<p>‚ÄúIt‚Äôs better to tell a good story than a perfect one. Consumer demand for authenticity is at an all-time high. As AI becomes more prevalent, it‚Äôs important to leverage it in ways to make more meaningful connections with customers. Do not use it just for the sake of using it. Consumers aren‚Äôt looking for businesses to cut corners, they are looking for value,‚Äù Tyler said.</p>
<h2>What these 2025 Facebook ads benchmarks mean for your strategy</h2>
<p>Use this industry data as a guideline to inform your strategy. These benchmarks can help you understand how your campaign performance might be pacing against your average competitor. This can be helpful when you want to make confident, data-backed marketing and advertising decisions this year and beyond.</p>
<p>If your results don‚Äôt always exactly match up to the averages in your industry, that‚Äôs okay! Just be ready to flex and shift your strategy as trends in your industry evolve. And, remember, you don‚Äôt have to manage the ups and downs of Facebook advertising all alone. See how <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/marketing-services?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Demo_Blog_Demo" target="_blank" rel="noopener">our solutions</a> can help transform your strategy into a goal-crushing machine.</p>
<h4>About the data</h4>
<p>The traffic objective data is based on a sample of 554 US-based search advertising campaigns running between April 1, 2024, and June 30, 2025. Each subcategory includes at minimum 3 unique active campaigns.</p>
<p>The leads objective data is based on a sample of 726 US-based search advertising campaigns running between April 1, 2024, and June 30, 2025. Each subcategory includes at minimum 2 unique active campaigns.</p>
<p>For both objectives, ‚Äúaverages‚Äù are technically median figures to account for outliers. All currency values are posted in USD.</p>
